  "suggestion": "[motivational-psychology+social-cognition+regulatory-theory+emotion-theory] IMPLEMENT NOW — Regulatory Focus Theory as 2-Axis Motivational Spine (Higgins 1997). Person gets two orthogonal parameters: promotionFocus ∈ [0,1] (approach gains, ideals, advancement) and preventionFocus ∈ [0,1] (avoid losses, duties, safety). Situation is classified as gain-framed (reward, success, opportunity) or loss-framed (threat, failure, criticism). regulatory_pressure = promotionFocus * gain_salience - preventionFocus * loss_salience. When pressure > 0: eagerness strategy, approach behavior, creative risk-taking, joy/excitement emotions. When pressure < 0: vigilance strategy, conservative behavior, status-quo bias, anxiety/guilt emotions. Infer promotionFocus from extraversion + openness; preventionFocus from neuroticism + conscientiousness. This single axis predicts which cognitive biases activate (omission bias, status quo → high prevention; optimism bias, planning fallacy → high promotion), which emotions arise (cheerfulness vs quiescence for promotion; agitation vs dejection for prevention), and which decisions are made. Maps cleanly to the existing domain-specific handlers with one new filter pass. — Math: regulatory_pressure = (promotionFocus × Σ gain_signals) − (preventionFocus × Σ loss_signals); eagerness_strategy iff pressure > 0; emotion_valence ∈ {cheerful, excited, dejected, anxious} determined by focus × outcome; [social-psychology+Bayesian-inference+information-theory+persuasion-theory] Social Proof as Bayesian Belief Update (Cialdini + Bayes). The model currently treats social setting as context but doesn't model how group behavior updates personal beliefs. When a person is uncertain, they weight social consensus as evidence. belief_posterior = (certainty × personal_prior + n_others × social_signal) / (certainty + n_others). certainty = 1 − person.arousal × neuroticism (arousal + neuroticism erode certainty). social_signal = inferred group consensus from socialSetting. Conformity pressure ≈ n_others / (certainty + n_others). This directly predicts: bystander effect (diffusion of responsibility when n_others is high and situation is ambiguous), Asch conformity (certainty collapse under unanimous opposition), informational vs normative influence (high certainty → normative only; low certainty → informational), and social anxiety (high arousal → certainty collapses → extreme conformity pressure). Person parameter: trait_conformity = agreeableness × 0.6 + neuroticism × 0.4. — Math: certainty = 1 − arousal × neuroticism; social_weight = n_others × trait_conformity; posterior = (certainty × prior + social_weight × consensus) / (certainty + social_weight); conformity_pressure = social_weight / (certainty + social_weight); [cognitive-psychology+social-cognition+temporal-reasoning+construal-theory] Construal Level Theory as Psychological Distance Lens (Trope & Liberman 2010). Psychological distance (temporal, social, hypothetical) determines whether thinking is concrete or abstract — and concrete vs abstract thinking generates categorically different responses. distance = temporal_distance_days / 365 + social_distance (self=0, acquaintance=0.5, stranger=1) + (1 − stimulus.personalRelevance). construal_level = 1 − 1/(1 + distance) → [0,1]. Low construal (near): response driven by concrete behaviors, immediate emotions, contextual feasibility, means-focused. High construal (far): response driven by abstract values, principles, goals, ends-focused. Implementation: after domain prediction, apply construal filter — low construal makes emotion and behavior outputs more specific/visceral; high construal makes rootCause output more value-principled and behavior more idealized. Explains why people make different moral choices about hypotheticals vs real events, why distant suffering generates less helping, why far-future commitments are bolder than near-future ones. — Math: distance = t/365 + social_d + (1 − relevance); construal = 1 − 1/(1+distance); behavior_specificity = 1 − construal; principle_weight = construal; final_response = lerp(concrete_template, abstract_template, construal)",
